LAGOS – A recent study conducted by the Nigerian Institute of Social and Economic Research (NISER), Ibadan, Oyo State, has revealed that irrespective of the government in power, infrastructure, innovation, health and primary education, higher education and training, technological readiness and institutions were bottommost on Nigeria’s development agenda between 2013 and 2017. Professor Joel Babatunde Babalola of the University of Ibadan, while speaking at the NISER monthly seminar series, revealed that to assess the weakest links in the chain of development in Nigeria, the paper focused on Nigeria’s policy prioritisation between 2013 and 2019 (covering Jonathan’s and Buhari’s Administrations) to see how much priority the country placed on education and training (skills), research (science), technology (ICT adoption) and innovation. “Nevertheless market size, labour market efficiency, macro-economic environment, good market, financial market and business sophistication top Nigeria’s development agenda between 2013 and 2017 The study also shows that in spite of Nigeria’s huge Gross Domestic Product (GDP), it performed below South Africa averages in all 2016 Gross Commission Incomes (GCIs), except in labour market and market size respectively. “This might in part be because South Africa approached her development in a more comprehensive manner than Nigeria did.